1
00:00:10,724 --> 00:00:13,793
[subtle piano music]

2
00:00:17,034 --> 00:00:19,758
[magical sounds]

3
00:00:27,068 --> 00:00:30,172
[subtle piano music]

4
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,931
- [Narrator] This is the
story about Christmas,

5
00:00:40,965 --> 00:00:43,034
the most special
time of the year,

6
00:00:44,931 --> 00:00:49,241
special for everybody in the
world, no matter who they are

7
00:00:49,275 --> 00:00:51,896
and this story happened
one Christmas Eve,

8
00:00:51,931 --> 00:00:56,551
a not so very long time ago,
far away in the mountains.

9
00:01:00,172 --> 00:01:03,586
[upbeat Christmas music]

10
00:01:18,896 --> 00:01:21,965
[subtle piano music]

11
00:01:30,758 --> 00:01:33,413
Now in this Christmas
story, there was a bear,

12
00:01:33,448 --> 00:01:38,448
and a raccoon, and a cougar,
and wolves, and a linx,

13
00:01:39,620 --> 00:01:41,551
and a fox, and a dog,
and a little girl.

14
00:01:45,241 --> 00:01:47,103
But I'm getting ahead of myself.

15
00:01:48,172 --> 00:01:49,586
Let's start at the beginning.

16
00:01:52,034 --> 00:01:55,344
It was a very cold day
that day before Christmas.

17
00:02:02,172 --> 00:02:03,931
Most of the animals
in the forest

18
00:02:03,965 --> 00:02:06,379
were busy getting ready
for that special day.

19
00:02:11,827 --> 00:02:13,241
Some more than others,

20
00:02:19,655 --> 00:02:22,896
but this story didn't
happen until that night,

21
00:02:22,931 --> 00:02:26,379
when a little girl read about
it in a magic storybook.

22
00:02:31,068 --> 00:02:34,103
The little girl's
name was Chrissy,

23
00:02:34,137 --> 00:02:36,758
she had just gone to
bed on Christmas Eve,

24
00:02:36,793 --> 00:02:40,413
but something very special
was about to happen to her.

25
00:02:40,448 --> 00:02:42,206
That was the Christmas
Eve she discovered

26
00:02:42,241 --> 00:02:44,931
The Magic Storybook.

27
00:02:46,137 --> 00:02:47,448
- [Child] Did you see that?

28
00:02:48,793 --> 00:02:50,000
- [Narrator] Well, actually

29
00:02:50,034 --> 00:02:51,586
The Magic Storybook
discovered her.

30
00:02:53,724 --> 00:02:55,758
- [Child] Check that out.

31
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,103
- [Child] Hey, it
jumped up on the bed.

32
00:03:01,137 --> 00:03:03,586
- [Narrator] The little
stuffed animals were right,

33
00:03:03,620 --> 00:03:06,310
The Magic Storybook
jumped right up on the bed

34
00:03:06,344 --> 00:03:08,448
and touched Chrissy on the nose.

35
00:03:08,482 --> 00:03:10,724
"How very strange" she thought.

36
00:03:10,758 --> 00:03:13,793
Well, she just had to
read it, wouldn't you?

37
00:03:13,827 --> 00:03:17,344
So Chrissy opened the book
up and read the first story

38
00:03:19,551 --> 00:03:22,896
and the first story was
Winslow, The Christmas Bear.

39
00:03:30,931 --> 00:03:33,862
It was just as Christmas
Eve day was beginning.

40
00:03:33,896 --> 00:03:36,034
It was very cold that morning,

41
00:03:36,068 --> 00:03:38,655
but the cold wasn't why
Winslow the bear wasn't asleep

42
00:03:38,689 --> 00:03:41,241
like all the other
bears in the forest.

43
00:03:41,275 --> 00:03:43,413
Winslow couldn't sleep.

44
00:03:43,448 --> 00:03:45,103
He was supposed to be sleeping.

45
00:03:45,137 --> 00:03:47,620
That's what bears do in
the winter, you know?

46
00:03:47,655 --> 00:03:49,931
But Winslow was much too excited

47
00:03:49,965 --> 00:03:52,724
to even think about
closing his eyes.

48
00:03:52,758 --> 00:03:56,655
You see, Winslow is quite
different from other bears.

49
00:03:56,689 --> 00:03:59,517
Winslow thought about
things very carefully

50
00:03:59,551 --> 00:04:02,620
and one of the things he
thought the most about

51
00:04:02,655 --> 00:04:04,137
was Christmas.

52
00:04:04,172 --> 00:04:07,586
- [Winslow] I wonder what
Christmas is really like.

53
00:04:07,620 --> 00:04:09,137
- [Narrator] That's what
Winslow asked himself

54
00:04:09,172 --> 00:04:12,241
because he really
wanted to know.

55
00:04:12,275 --> 00:04:15,310
- [Winslow] Well, I can't
find out if I'm sleeping.

56
00:04:15,344 --> 00:04:16,655
- [Narrator] Of
course he was right.

57
00:04:16,689 --> 00:04:18,931
He couldn't find out
if he was sleeping.

58
00:04:18,965 --> 00:04:22,103
So that morning, Winslow
had decided to find out

59
00:04:22,137 --> 00:04:23,965
what Christmas really was

60
00:04:26,206 --> 00:04:28,137
and that's exactly what he did.

61
00:04:29,482 --> 00:04:32,068
- [Winslow] My, it's
awfully quiet this morning.

62
00:04:32,103 --> 00:04:33,965
I haven't seen anybody.

63
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:37,137
Oh, it's Wild Bill the Buffalo.

64
00:04:37,172 --> 00:04:40,413
Hey Wild Bill, I want
to ask you a question.

65
00:04:42,413 --> 00:04:44,724
Oh, the river sure is wide here.

66
00:04:44,758 --> 00:04:46,827
How am I going to get across?

67
00:04:46,862 --> 00:04:49,344
I need to ask Wild
Bill what Christmas is.

68
00:04:50,517 --> 00:04:53,551
Oh, it's hard to
walk on this long.

69
00:04:53,586 --> 00:04:55,034
I can't, whoa, whoa.

70
00:04:58,413 --> 00:05:00,275
That water is cold.

71
00:05:00,310 --> 00:05:02,931
Wild Bill, it's me Winslow.

72
00:05:02,965 --> 00:05:04,413
Oh, wait Wild Bill.

73
00:05:04,448 --> 00:05:05,655
Wait, I need to ask you.

74
00:05:06,827 --> 00:05:07,655
Please don't go.

75
00:05:08,793 --> 00:05:10,689
I need to know
what Christmas is.

76
00:05:11,551 --> 00:05:13,448
Oh, that water is cold.

77
00:05:14,344 --> 00:05:17,034
Oh no, he's gone.

78
00:05:17,068 --> 00:05:18,379
Who can I ask now?

79
00:05:19,724 --> 00:05:21,724
- [Narrator] Winslow
thought about it.

80
00:05:21,758 --> 00:05:22,896
What should he do?

81
00:05:22,931 --> 00:05:24,413
Who should he ask?

82
00:05:24,448 --> 00:05:26,586
- [Winslow] I bet my
friend Roger Raccoon

83
00:05:26,620 --> 00:05:28,758
would know what Christmas is.

84
00:05:28,793 --> 00:05:30,689
I'll go ask him.

85
00:05:30,724 --> 00:05:32,931
- [Narrator] And that's
exactly what he did.

86
00:05:44,034 --> 00:05:46,448
After Winslow had been
traveling quite a while,

87
00:05:46,482 --> 00:05:48,551
he came upon a fallen
tree in the forest

88
00:05:48,586 --> 00:05:50,310
and started over it.

89
00:05:50,344 --> 00:05:53,275
It was right then that
he saw his friend, Roger.

90
00:05:53,310 --> 00:05:56,448
Now, Roger a very
busy little raccoon.

91
00:05:56,482 --> 00:05:59,068
He was gathering food
on this cold winter day,

92
00:05:59,103 --> 00:06:01,275
busy, busy, busy.

93
00:06:01,310 --> 00:06:02,551
- [Winslow] Hi Roger.

94
00:06:02,586 --> 00:06:04,206
- [Roger] Hey Winslow,
what are you doing up?

95
00:06:04,241 --> 00:06:06,310
Bears aren't supposed to
be awake during the winter.

96
00:06:06,344 --> 00:06:08,620
You're supposed to be
in your cave asleep.

97
00:06:08,655 --> 00:06:09,827
- [Winslow] I know,

98
00:06:09,862 --> 00:06:12,000
but I want to find
out what Christmas is.

99
00:06:12,034 --> 00:06:14,862
- [Roger] You don't
know what Christmas is?

100
00:06:14,896 --> 00:06:16,172
How very strange.

101
00:06:16,206 --> 00:06:18,172
- [Winslow] That's
why I came to visit.

102
00:06:18,206 --> 00:06:20,724
I thought that maybe
you could tell me.

103
00:06:20,758 --> 00:06:21,931
- [Roger] Well, I really
don't have a lot of time

104
00:06:21,965 --> 00:06:23,655
to talk right now
because I'm very busy.

105
00:06:23,689 --> 00:06:24,931
See, busy?

106
00:06:24,965 --> 00:06:26,344
But if you want to
know what I think,

107
00:06:26,379 --> 00:06:30,413
I think Christmas is
food, good things to eat.

108
00:06:30,448 --> 00:06:33,103
Yeah, that's what it
is all right, food.

109
00:06:33,137 --> 00:06:34,379
- [Narrator] Roger
kept gathering up

110
00:06:34,413 --> 00:06:36,965
all the small nuts and
berries he could find.

111
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,103
Winslow thought very
hard for a moment

112
00:06:40,137 --> 00:06:42,241
about what Roger had said.

113
00:06:42,275 --> 00:06:45,172
- [Roger] Look, if
you don't believe me,

114
00:06:45,206 --> 00:06:46,724
why don't you go
ask Frieda the Fox?

115
00:06:46,758 --> 00:06:49,034
She's very clever, I
bet she could help you.

116
00:06:50,413 --> 00:06:52,448
- [Winslow] That's a good idea.

117
00:06:52,482 --> 00:06:54,241
- [Roger] But you better
be careful Winslow.

118
00:06:54,275 --> 00:06:56,482
- [Winslow] Well,
why do you say that?

119
00:06:56,517 --> 00:06:58,551
- [Roger] Cause the
wolf family is out

120
00:06:58,586 --> 00:07:01,620
and you don't want to end up
being their supper, do you?

121
00:07:01,655 --> 00:07:03,172
- [Winslow] No, I guess I don't.

122
00:07:03,206 --> 00:07:05,068
Thanks for telling me, Roger.

123
00:07:05,103 --> 00:07:06,862
- [Roger] Any time fuzz brain.

124
00:07:06,896 --> 00:07:08,586
Don't take any chances.

125
00:07:08,620 --> 00:07:10,655
- [Winslow] I'm
going to see Frieda.

126
00:07:10,689 --> 00:07:13,793
- [Narrator] And that's
exactly what he did.

127
00:07:13,827 --> 00:07:15,862
Winslow didn't really
think about the wolves

128
00:07:15,896 --> 00:07:18,655
as he walked away, he was
too busy trying to decide

129
00:07:18,689 --> 00:07:20,448
what to ask Frieda the Fox.

130
00:07:22,655 --> 00:07:25,413
But the wolves were
out that Christmas Eve

131
00:07:25,448 --> 00:07:28,034
and they were
looking for Winslow.

132
00:07:28,068 --> 00:07:30,482
Winslow was walking right
through the very place

133
00:07:30,517 --> 00:07:32,689
where the wolf family lived.

134
00:07:32,724 --> 00:07:35,310
Winslow decided he'd
better be very careful

135
00:07:35,344 --> 00:07:37,206
because he didn't want
to end up as dinner

136
00:07:37,241 --> 00:07:39,000
for a pack of hungry wolves.

137
00:07:42,034 --> 00:07:44,000
Suddenly, there
was Frieda the Fox,

138
00:07:44,034 --> 00:07:45,931
Winslow's very good friend.

139
00:07:47,344 --> 00:07:50,517
- [Frieda] Oh my word, is
that Winslow the Bear I see?

140
00:07:50,551 --> 00:07:51,931
- [Winslow] It's me.

141
00:07:51,965 --> 00:07:54,448
I've come to ask you a
very important question.

142
00:07:54,482 --> 00:07:56,275
- [Frieda] What
important question?

143
00:07:56,310 --> 00:07:59,000
- [Winslow] I want to
know what Christmas is.

144
00:07:59,034 --> 00:08:01,482
Boy, your fur sure is soft.

145
00:08:01,517 --> 00:08:02,344
I'm sorry.

146
00:08:03,482 --> 00:08:05,206
Did I say something wrong?

147
00:08:05,241 --> 00:08:06,448
- [Frieda] You mean to tell me

148
00:08:06,482 --> 00:08:08,482
you came all this way
from your warm cave

149
00:08:08,517 --> 00:08:10,310
to ask me what Christmas is?

150
00:08:10,344 --> 00:08:12,931
That's easy, Christmas
is having fun.

151
00:08:12,965 --> 00:08:15,344
- [Winslow] Having fun,
that's what Christmas is?

152
00:08:15,379 --> 00:08:16,620
- [Frieda] Sure Winslow.

153
00:08:16,655 --> 00:08:18,103
I have the most wonderful time

154
00:08:18,137 --> 00:08:20,206
exploring and playing
in this thicket.

155
00:08:20,241 --> 00:08:22,379
There's so much to do and see.

156
00:08:22,413 --> 00:08:25,482
Besides, Christmas is the
happiest time of the year.

157
00:08:25,517 --> 00:08:27,241
- [Winslow] So
Christmas is having fun.

158
00:08:27,275 --> 00:08:28,517
Can't you stand still?

159
00:08:28,551 --> 00:08:30,551
- [Frieda] Can't, no
fun to stand around

160
00:08:30,586 --> 00:08:32,931
and having fun is the
most important thing.

161
00:08:32,965 --> 00:08:34,896
- [Narrator] As
soon as she said it,

162
00:08:34,931 --> 00:08:38,689
Frieda became a bundle of
energy running here and there

163
00:08:38,724 --> 00:08:41,275
while poor Winslow could
hardly even follow her.

164
00:08:41,310 --> 00:08:43,517
He tried to stop
her with his paw,

165
00:08:43,551 --> 00:08:45,172
but she was much too quick.

166
00:08:45,206 --> 00:08:47,689
- [Frieda] I know who else
you could ask, Winslow.

167
00:08:47,724 --> 00:08:49,931
You could ask cranky old
Wilford the Wolverine.

168
00:08:49,965 --> 00:08:51,344
- [Winslow] I could, couldn't I?

169
00:08:51,379 --> 00:08:53,517
I'll just go ask old Wilford.

170
00:08:53,551 --> 00:08:54,862
Thank you, Frieda.

171
00:08:54,896 --> 00:08:55,689
- [Frieda] You're welcome.

172
00:08:55,724 --> 00:08:56,551
And Winslow?

173
00:08:56,586 --> 00:08:57,793
- [Winslow] Yes?

174
00:08:57,827 --> 00:08:58,965
- [Frieda] There's
one more thing.

175
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:00,379
- [Winslow] What's that, Frieda?

176
00:09:00,413 --> 00:09:01,827
- [Frieda] Be very careful.

177
00:09:01,862 --> 00:09:03,862
The wolf family's looking
for Christmas dinner

178
00:09:03,896 --> 00:09:06,413
and you don't want to be
the main course, do you?

179
00:09:06,448 --> 00:09:07,586
- [Winslow] No, I don't.

180
00:09:07,620 --> 00:09:08,827
I'll be careful.

181
00:09:08,862 --> 00:09:10,206
- [Frieda] Have a
merry Christmas.

182
00:09:10,241 --> 00:09:11,689
- [Winslow] Thank you very much.

183
00:09:11,724 --> 00:09:13,586
I will, I think.

184
00:09:14,793 --> 00:09:16,379
- [Frieda] Winslow is
such a funny old bear.

185
00:09:16,413 --> 00:09:18,275
I hope he's okay.

186
00:09:18,310 --> 00:09:19,862
- [Narrator] Frieda was right.

187
00:09:19,896 --> 00:09:22,344
The wolf family was
lurking around the forest

188
00:09:22,379 --> 00:09:25,689
on that Christmas Eve and
they were looking for Winslow.

189
00:09:25,724 --> 00:09:28,448
Chrissy put down the book
for a moment, concerned.

190
00:09:28,482 --> 00:09:30,413
The wolves made her
afraid for Winslow.

191
00:09:30,448 --> 00:09:32,103
What could he do?

192
00:09:32,137 --> 00:09:33,724
She hoped he'd be all right.

193
00:09:35,448 --> 00:09:38,034
On his way, Winslow
got a little lost

194
00:09:38,068 --> 00:09:40,896
so he stopped to ask
directions from a fisher.

195
00:09:40,931 --> 00:09:43,931
Dolly was in a tree, so
Winslow poked his nose

196
00:09:43,965 --> 00:09:45,241
right up in the branches.

197
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:48,275
- [Winslow] Hello Dolly.

198
00:09:48,310 --> 00:09:50,827
Can you tell me how
to get to the meadow?

199
00:09:50,862 --> 00:09:52,551
- [Dolly] Sure
Winslow, it's that way

200
00:09:52,586 --> 00:09:55,275
down in the valley
by the big trees.

201
00:09:55,310 --> 00:09:57,827
Hey, what are you
doing here anyway?

202
00:09:57,862 --> 00:09:59,241
- [Winslow] Looking for Wilford.

203
00:09:59,275 --> 00:10:00,413
Thank you, Dolly.

204
00:10:04,724 --> 00:10:07,172
- [Narrator] Winslow had
to travel for a long way

205
00:10:07,206 --> 00:10:09,965
because the valley in the
mountains was quite large.

206
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,103
Sometimes he had to
squeeze his big bear body

207
00:10:13,137 --> 00:10:15,206
through very small openings,

208
00:10:15,241 --> 00:10:17,034
but that didn't stop Winslow

209
00:10:17,068 --> 00:10:20,586
because he really wanted
to know what Christmas was.

210
00:10:20,620 --> 00:10:22,103
As he traveled, as he traveled,

211
00:10:22,137 --> 00:10:23,586
he thought to himself

212
00:10:23,620 --> 00:10:26,241
that maybe he shouldn't have
left his nice warm cave.

213
00:10:26,275 --> 00:10:28,103
Just like everybody said,

214
00:10:28,137 --> 00:10:30,379
bears weren't supposed
to be out on Christmas.

215
00:10:30,413 --> 00:10:31,379
Maybe they were right.

216
00:10:31,413 --> 00:10:33,068
But then he thought.

217
00:10:33,103 --> 00:10:36,310
- [Winslow] Well how will
I know if I don't find out?

218
00:10:36,344 --> 00:10:38,206
- [Narrator] And so,
he kept on going.

219
00:10:43,551 --> 00:10:45,034
- [Oliver] Here I go.

220
00:10:45,068 --> 00:10:47,586
Gotta get in the water.

221
00:10:47,620 --> 00:10:49,655
Ah, the big splash, yeah!

222
00:10:51,586 --> 00:10:53,689
Oh yeah, Geronimo!

223
00:10:53,724 --> 00:10:54,517
Woo!

224
00:10:57,344 --> 00:10:59,586
Great day for a swim.

225
00:11:00,827 --> 00:11:02,310
- [Narrator] Winslow
was hurrying along

226
00:11:02,344 --> 00:11:04,551
when he heard Oliver, the
quick little river otter,

227
00:11:04,586 --> 00:11:08,344
having the time of his life
swimming in the mountain stream.

228
00:11:08,379 --> 00:11:10,862
Oliver was one of
Winslow's best friends

229
00:11:10,896 --> 00:11:15,000
and oh, how Oliver loved to
dive and play in the water

230
00:11:15,034 --> 00:11:18,034
during the winter because
an otter and water

231
00:11:18,068 --> 00:11:21,310
just go together, even
in a cold winter stream.

232
00:11:29,206 --> 00:11:30,448
Winslow was going along

233
00:11:30,482 --> 00:11:32,862
as fast as his bear
legs could carry him

234
00:11:32,896 --> 00:11:34,620
when he finally saw Oliver.

235
00:11:36,275 --> 00:11:37,517
- [Oliver] Wee!

236
00:11:38,724 --> 00:11:40,310
- [Winslow] There's Oliver now.

237
00:11:40,344 --> 00:11:41,896
Hello Oliver.

238
00:11:41,931 --> 00:11:44,310
- [Oliver] Hey
Winslow, is that you?

239
00:11:44,344 --> 00:11:46,620
- [Winslow] Oliver Otter,
what are you doing?

240
00:11:46,655 --> 00:11:48,965
- [Oliver] Well, I'm
not getting dry cleaned.

241
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,137
- [Winslow] Oh, isn't that cold?

242
00:11:52,172 --> 00:11:53,724
- [Oliver] Otters love water.

243
00:11:53,758 --> 00:11:56,551
We have very heavy fur coats
and water can't get through.

244
00:11:56,586 --> 00:11:59,689
Hey, why aren't you asleep in
your cave with your mother?

245
00:11:59,724 --> 00:12:03,310
- [Winslow] Oh, I'm asking
everyone what Christmas is.

246
00:12:03,344 --> 00:12:04,620
- [Oliver] What Christmas is?

247
00:12:04,655 --> 00:12:06,586
Christmas is getting
everything that's good.

248
00:12:06,620 --> 00:12:08,551
Don't you know that, bear brain?

249
00:12:08,586 --> 00:12:11,068
- [Winslow] Christmas
is all those things?

250
00:12:11,103 --> 00:12:12,758
I don't understand.

251
00:12:12,793 --> 00:12:14,137
- [Oliver] Christmas
is whatever good thing

252
00:12:14,172 --> 00:12:15,379
you want it to be.

253
00:12:15,413 --> 00:12:17,068
I thought everybody knew that.

254
00:12:17,103 --> 00:12:19,137
- [Winslow] Well,
I didn't know that.

255
00:12:19,172 --> 00:12:20,344
- [Oliver] That's because bears

256
00:12:20,379 --> 00:12:22,344
are supposed to be
asleep in the winter.

257
00:12:22,379 --> 00:12:24,034
Boy, are you slow.

258
00:12:24,068 --> 00:12:26,965
Besides, bears aren't meant
to celebrate Christmas.

259
00:12:29,310 --> 00:12:30,758
- [Winslow] What's so funny?

260
00:12:30,793 --> 00:12:34,034
- [Oliver] Oh, the
snow tickles my back.

261
00:12:34,068 --> 00:12:36,689
Winslow, bears hibernate
during the winter,

262
00:12:36,724 --> 00:12:39,034
they don't have to
worry about Christmas.

263
00:12:39,068 --> 00:12:41,482
- [Winslow] I thought
Christmas was for everybody.

264
00:12:41,517 --> 00:12:43,724
- [Oliver] I don't think
Christmas is for bears.

265
00:12:43,758 --> 00:12:47,448
In fact, I don't think any bear
has even tried to find out.

266
00:12:47,482 --> 00:12:49,000
- [Narrator] That
was news to Winslow.

267
00:12:49,034 --> 00:12:51,103
He didn't want to do
anything he shouldn't.

268
00:12:51,137 --> 00:12:53,793
- [Winslow] I didn't know
I wasn't supposed to.

269
00:12:53,827 --> 00:12:56,827
- [Oliver] Hey,
where are you going?

270
00:12:56,862 --> 00:12:59,310
- [Winslow] Well, I guess
I better go back home.

271
00:12:59,344 --> 00:13:00,655
- [Oliver] Gee, now
that you're here,

272
00:13:00,689 --> 00:13:02,517
you might as well go
and ask old Wilford,

273
00:13:02,551 --> 00:13:03,931
even though he is pretty cranky

274
00:13:03,965 --> 00:13:05,724
about these things sometimes.

275
00:13:05,758 --> 00:13:07,206
- [Winslow] Oh, that's true.

276
00:13:07,241 --> 00:13:10,310
But maybe I'll just ask him,
as long as I've come this far.

277
00:13:10,344 --> 00:13:12,620
- [Oliver] Good idea, fur face.

278
00:13:12,655 --> 00:13:16,206
Take care of yourself and have
a merry Christmas Winslow.

279
00:13:16,241 --> 00:13:17,931
- [Winslow] Thank you.

280
00:13:17,965 --> 00:13:19,206
I will, I hope.

281
00:13:20,620 --> 00:13:21,793
- [Narrator] And with that,

282
00:13:21,827 --> 00:13:23,000
Oliver plopped into the
icy cold water again

283
00:13:23,034 --> 00:13:25,000
and swam to the other shore.

284
00:13:26,793 --> 00:13:28,448
As Winslow watched Oliver go,

285
00:13:28,482 --> 00:13:30,793
he thought about those
hungry wolves again

286
00:13:30,827 --> 00:13:34,034
and his very big bear
heart gave a thump.

287
00:13:37,379 --> 00:13:38,896
Oliver hopped out of the water

288
00:13:38,931 --> 00:13:41,655
and started scurrying here
and there up the hill,

289
00:13:41,689 --> 00:13:43,758
in and out.

290
00:13:43,793 --> 00:13:45,241
It was Christmas
Eve and of course,

291
00:13:45,275 --> 00:13:46,862
Oliver had a great
many things to do

292
00:13:46,896 --> 00:13:48,068
before the big day came.

293
00:13:51,482 --> 00:13:54,241
So Winslow the Bear
continued his journey

294
00:13:54,275 --> 00:13:56,448
on that Christmas Eve day.

295
00:13:56,482 --> 00:14:00,241
He was thinking about all the
things he'd learned so far.

296
00:14:00,275 --> 00:14:03,379
Roger had told him
Christmas was about food.

297
00:14:03,413 --> 00:14:06,586
Frieda said that Christmas
was exploring new things.

298
00:14:06,620 --> 00:14:07,965
Oliver told him that Christmas

299
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
was just what you
want to make it.

300
00:14:11,034 --> 00:14:13,310
Poor Winslow was so confused.

301
00:14:13,344 --> 00:14:14,793
He didn't know what to think.

302
00:14:14,827 --> 00:14:16,034
Who was right?

303
00:14:16,068 --> 00:14:18,000
Then, just as
Winslow was wondering

304
00:14:18,034 --> 00:14:20,241
about all those things
His friends had told him,

305
00:14:20,275 --> 00:14:23,517
he saw old Wilford
the Wolverine.

306
00:14:23,551 --> 00:14:26,896
He certainly did look
cranky, Winslow had to admit.

307
00:14:26,931 --> 00:14:29,275
At first, he didn't think
he was going to say anything

308
00:14:29,310 --> 00:14:30,517
to the cranky old Wilford,

309
00:14:30,551 --> 00:14:33,241
but then his curiosity
about Christmas

310
00:14:33,275 --> 00:14:35,241
got the better of him.

311
00:14:35,275 --> 00:14:36,275
- [Winslow] Hello Wilford.

312
00:14:36,310 --> 00:14:37,793
- [Wilford] What do you want?

313
00:14:37,827 --> 00:14:39,965
Haven't got time to dilly
dally with the likes of you.

314
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:41,517
Things to do, places to go.

315
00:14:41,551 --> 00:14:43,137
- [Winslow] I'm
sorry to bother you.

316
00:14:43,172 --> 00:14:45,827
I was just wandering
what Christmas was.

317
00:14:45,862 --> 00:14:47,103
- [Wilford] That's a
pretty silly question,

318
00:14:47,137 --> 00:14:48,137
what Christmas is.

319
00:14:48,172 --> 00:14:50,137
[mumbling]

320
00:14:50,172 --> 00:14:53,103
What do you want
to know for anyway?

321
00:14:53,137 --> 00:14:55,517
You're a bear, bears
don't have Christmas.

322
00:14:55,551 --> 00:14:57,586
You're supposed to be
asleep during Christmas.

323
00:14:57,620 --> 00:14:59,689
- [Winslow] Well, I
wasn't very tired.

324
00:14:59,724 --> 00:15:02,965
Everybody says Christmas
is something different

325
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:05,034
and I was hoping
you could tell me.

326
00:15:05,068 --> 00:15:06,310
- [Wilford] Don't
have time for this.

327
00:15:06,344 --> 00:15:08,517
Christmas is a waste of
time, that's what it is.

328
00:15:08,551 --> 00:15:11,413
- [Winslow] Well there must be
something you could tell me.

329
00:15:11,448 --> 00:15:12,482
- [Wilford] I could tell
you a lot of things,

330
00:15:12,517 --> 00:15:14,310
but I don't want to.

331
00:15:14,344 --> 00:15:17,137
Not my job to tell every
fuzz ball that comes along

332
00:15:17,172 --> 00:15:19,068
what Christmas is, not my job.

333
00:15:19,103 --> 00:15:20,724
- [Winslow] Well, could
you give me a hint?

334
00:15:20,758 --> 00:15:22,620
I won't bother you anymore.

335
00:15:22,655 --> 00:15:23,896
- [Wilford] Too late,

336
00:15:23,931 --> 00:15:25,379
this is all a lot of
bother and bladder,

337
00:15:25,413 --> 00:15:28,827
bother and bladder, bother and
bladder, that's what it is.

338
00:15:28,862 --> 00:15:30,310
No time for this.

339
00:15:30,344 --> 00:15:32,827
- [Narrator] Said Wilford and
he was gone just like that.

340
00:15:32,862 --> 00:15:35,965
Winslow just sat there
more confused than ever.

341
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:37,517
That didn't sound
like the Christmas

342
00:15:37,551 --> 00:15:38,827
he'd always heard about.

343
00:15:38,862 --> 00:15:41,620
- [Winslow] I'll just go
ask someone else then.

344
00:15:41,655 --> 00:15:43,482
- [Narrator] He said to
himself as he trotted away

345
00:15:43,517 --> 00:15:45,896
and that's exactly what he did.

346
00:15:47,896 --> 00:15:51,310
[upbeat Christmas music]

347
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:00,000
♪ Winslow the Christmas bear

